# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 SQLite — Formal Academic Definition

**SQLite** is a **serverless, self-contained, transactional SQL database engine** embedded directly into an Android application. It is the default, built-in relational database management system (RDBMS) provided by the Android SDK through the `android.database.sqlite` package. Unlike client-server databases, SQLite reads and writes directly to ordinary disk files, requiring no separate database server process.

In the KTU 2024 Scheme syllabus, SQLite is treated as the **local persistence layer** for mobile applications, used when data is structured, relational, and confined to a single device.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Key Syllabus Definition (KTU 2024):** SQLite is a C-language library that implements a small, fast, self-contained, high-reliability, full-featured SQL database engine. It is the most widely deployed database in the world — present in every Android device, iPhone, browser, and operating system.

## 1.2 Firebase Realtime Database — Formal Academic Definition

**Firebase Realtime Database (RTDB)** is a **cloud-hosted NoSQL document database** where data is stored as a **JSON tree** and synchronized in real time to every connected client. It is part of Google's Firebase platform (Backend-as-a-Service / BaaS) and is accessed in Android applications via the Firebase SDK.

Data is stored as one large JSON tree, and when any client updates a node, all connected clients receive the update within milliseconds — a paradigm called **real-time synchronization**.

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Syllabus Definition (KTU 2024):** Firebase Realtime Database is a cloud-hosted NoSQL database that stores data in JSON format, supports offline persistence, and synchronizes data across multiple clients in real time using a WebSocket-based connection.

## 1.3 Conceptual Analogy — Plain English Intuition

### 🍱 The "Pantry vs. Cloud Notebook" Analogy

Imagine you are a student maintaining two notebooks:

- **Notebook A (Your Backpack)** → **SQLite**  
  You carry it everywhere, write in it with a pen, and only YOU can read it. If you lose the backpack, the notes are gone. Fast, private, offline, no internet needed.

- **Notebook B (Google Docs)** → **Firebase RTDB**  
  You share a Google Doc with friends. When you type a new line, your friends see it *instantly* without refreshing. It's stored on Google's servers, accessible from any device, and works only when you have internet (or syncs when you reconnect).

> [!TIP]
> **Rule of Thumb for Exams:**  
> - **Use SQLite** → when data is private, structured into tables, and needed offline.  
> - **Use Firebase RTDB** → when multiple users must see the same data live (chat apps, collaborative apps, live dashboards).

## 1.4 Standard Metrics & Parameters

| Parameter | SQLite | Firebase RTDB |
|---|---|---|
| **Storage Type** | Local file (`.db` / `.sqlite`) | Cloud JSON tree |
| **Architecture** | Relational (tables, rows, columns) | Document / NoSQL (key-value tree) |
| **Internet Required** | **No** | **Yes** (with offline cache) |
| **Concurrent Users** | Single device | **Millions** (multi-device sync) |
| **Query Language** | SQL | Firebase Queries (limited) |
| **License** | Public Domain | Proprietary (Google) |
| **Default Android DB** | **Yes** | No (requires Firebase setup) |
| **Storage Limit** | Device storage | **1 GB free tier** (Spark plan) |

## 1.5 Why Two Databases? — The Persistence Spectrum

Mobile applications rarely use just one storage mechanism. The KTU 2024 Scheme expects students to understand the **persistence hierarchy**:

1. **SharedPreferences** → key-value pairs (tiny settings, tokens)
2. **Internal/External File Storage** → files, images, logs
3. **SQLite** → structured relational local data
4. **Firebase RTDB** → real-time multi-user cloud data
5. **Firebase Firestore** → next-gen scalable cloud DB (beyond syllabus scope)

This lab session focuses on layers **3 and 4**.

