# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 SQLite — Deep Architecture Breakdown

SQLite in Android is implemented via two key classes:

### A. `SQLiteOpenHelper` (The Gatekeeper)

A helper class that manages **database creation** and **version management**. You extend it to:

- Define `onCreate()` → executes the first time the DB is opened.
- Define `onUpgrade()` → executes when the DB version is incremented.

### B. `SQLiteDatabase` (The Workbench)

Provides methods to:
- `execSQL()` → execute raw SQL (CREATE, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE)
- `insert()`, `update()`, `delete()` → high-level CRUD via `ContentValues`
- `query()` → returns a `Cursor` for SELECT operations

### C. `Cursor` (The Result Handle)

A pointer that traverses row-by-row through query results. Methods include:
- `moveToFirst()`, `moveToNext()`
- `getString()`, `getInt()`, `getDouble()`
- `getColumnIndex()`

### D. `ContentValues` (The Row Mapper)

A key-value map mirroring a single row. Used with `insert()` and `update()`.

## 2.2 SQLite — Operational Logic (Why & How)

| Step | Why | How |
|---|---|---|
| **1. Extend `SQLiteOpenHelper`** | Centralize DB lifecycle | Override `onCreate()` & `onUpgrade()` |
| **2. Define schema in `onCreate()`** | Create tables once | `db.execSQL("CREATE TABLE ...")` |
| **3. Get writable/readable DB** | Open connection | `helper.getWritableDatabase()` / `getReadableDatabase()` |
| **4. Insert data** | Add rows | `ContentValues` + `db.insert()` |
| **5. Read data** | Fetch rows | `db.query()` returns `Cursor` |
| **6. Update data** | Modify rows | `db.update(CV, whereClause, whereArgs)` |
| **7. Delete data** | Remove rows | `db.delete(table, whereClause, whereArgs)` |
| **8. Close DB** | Release resources | `db.close()` / `cursor.close()` |

## 2.3 Firebase Realtime Database — Deep Architecture Breakdown

### A. Data Model — The JSON Tree

Firebase RTDB stores the **entire database as a single JSON tree**. There are no tables or rows; instead, data lives at **path nodes**.

Example JSON tree:
```json
{
  "users": {
    "user1": {
      "name": "Aiswarya",
      "email": "aiswarya@ktu.in",
      "score": 95
    },
    "user2": {
      "name": "Rahul",
      "email": "rahul@ktu.in",
      "score": 88
    }
  },
  "leaderboard": {
    "rank1": "Aiswarya",
    "rank2": "Rahul"
  }
}
```

### B. Core SDK Classes

| Class | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `FirebaseDatabase` | Singleton entry point to the DB instance |
| `DatabaseReference` | Pointer to a specific path/node in the JSON tree |
| `ValueEventListener` | Listens to data changes at a reference (once or continuously) |
| `ChildEventListener` | Listens to events on children: `onChildAdded`, `onChildChanged`, `onChildRemoved`, `onChildMoved` |
| `Query` | Used to order, filter, or limit data (`orderByChild`, `equalTo`, `limitToFirst`) |
| `DataSnapshot` | Contains data at a location at a single point in time |

### C. Write Operations

| Method | Use Case |
|---|---|
| `setValue()` | Replace data at the path |
| `push()` | Append a new child with a unique auto-generated key |
| `updateChildren()` | Update multiple nodes atomically |
| `removeValue()` | Delete a node |

### D. Read Operations

| Method | Use Case |
|---|---|
| `addValueEventListener()` | Continuous real-time updates |
| `addListenerForSingleValueEvent()` | Read once and detach |
| `addChildEventListener()` | Listen to child-level events |

## 2.4 KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet — Formula / Syntax Reference

| Concept | Syntax (Java) | Returns |
|---|---|---|
| **Create Table** | `db.execSQL("CREATE TABLE Student(id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT)")` | void |
| **Insert** | `db.insert("Student", null, cv)` | `long` (row ID, -1 on error) |
| **Update** | `db.update("Student", cv, "id=?", new String[]{"1"})` | `int` (rows affected) |
| **Delete** | `db.delete("Student", "id=?", new String[]{"1"})` | `int` (rows affected) |
| **Query** | `db.query("Student", null, null, null, null, null, null)` | `Cursor` |
| **Firebase Init** | `FirebaseDatabase.getInstance()` | `FirebaseDatabase` |
| **Reference** | `db.getReference("users/user1")` | `DatabaseReference` |
| **Set Value** | `ref.setValue("Aiswarya")` | `Task<Void>` |
| **Push Child** | `ref.push().setValue(data)` | `Task<Void>` |
| **Read Once** | `ref.addListenerForSingleValueEvent(listener)` | void (async) |
| **Read Live** | `ref.addValueEventListener(listener)` | void (async) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Exam Trivia (KTU Pattern):**  
> - In SQLite, `onUpgrade()` is triggered **only** when the version number passed to the `SQLiteOpenHelper` superclass constructor is **higher** than the existing version.  
> - In Firebase, `setValue(null)` is equivalent to `removeValue()`.  
> - Firebase RTDB is **schemaless** — you can store any valid JSON value (string, number, boolean, array, object) at any node.

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **SQLite** powers millions of apps for: contact lists, note-taking (Google Keep offline), to-do lists, expense trackers, inventory apps.
- **Firebase RTDB** powers: WhatsApp-style chat clients, collaborative whiteboards (Ex: Figma-lite), live sports score apps, IoT sensor dashboards, multiplayer game lobbies, and the famous **"Collaborative Drawing"** lab demo used in KTU viva voce.

