# SECTION 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

---

## 📝 PART A — 3-Mark Questions (Short Answer)

### Q1. `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]`
**Differentiate between SQLite and Firebase Realtime Database with respect to storage model, internet dependency, and concurrency support.**

**Model Answer:**

| Parameter | SQLite | Firebase RTDB |
|---|---|---|
| **Storage Model** | Relational tables (rows & columns) | JSON tree (key-value nodes) |
| **Internet Dependency** | None — fully offline | Required (with offline cache) |
| **Concurrency** | Single device, single user | Multi-device, multi-user real-time sync |

SQLite is best for **local, private, structured data**, while Firebase RTDB is best for **cloud-synchronized, multi-user, real-time applications**.

---

### Q2. `[KTU University Exam – June 2024]`
**What is the role of the `SQLiteOpenHelper` class in Android? Name its two important overridden methods.**

**Model Answer:**

`SQLiteOpenHelper` is a helper class that manages **database creation and version management** for SQLite in Android. It abstracts the low-level database lifecycle from the developer.

The two key methods to override are:

1. **`onCreate(SQLiteDatabase db)`** — Called the first time the database is accessed. Used to create tables using `db.execSQL()`.
2. **`onUpgrade(SQLiteDatabase db, int oldV, int newV)`** — Called when the database version number is incremented. Used to migrate the schema (e.g., drop and recreate tables).

---

## 📝 PART B — 14-Mark Questions (Module Internal Choice)

---

### ❓ Question A (14 Marks) `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2024]`

**(a) Design a SQLite database schema for an Android "Library Book Manager" app that stores book details (id, title, author, year, available). Write a complete `DBHelper` class implementing Insert, View All, Update, and Delete operations. [7 Marks]**

**(b) Explain the architecture of Firebase Realtime Database. Write the Java code to push a new record with auto-generated unique key and read all records in real time. [7 Marks]**

---

#### ✅ Model Solution for (a)

**Schema Design:**

```sql
CREATE TABLE book (
    id        INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    title     TEXT,
    author    TEXT,
    year      INTEGER,
    available INTEGER   -- 0 = no, 1 = yes
);
```

**DBHelper.java:**

```java
public class DBHelper extends SQLiteOpenHelper {
    private static final String DB = "libraryDB";
    private static final int VER = 1;
    private static final String TBL = "book";

    public DBHelper(Context c) { super(c, DB, null, VER); }

    @Override
    public void onCreate(SQLiteDatabase db) {
        db.execSQL("CREATE TABLE " + TBL + " (" +
                   "id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, " +
                   "title TEXT, author TEXT, year INTEGER, available INTEGER)");
    }

    @Override
    public void onUpgrade(SQLiteDatabase db, int o, int n) {
        db.execSQL("DROP TABLE IF EXISTS " + TBL);
        onCreate(db);
    }

    // INSERT
    public boolean insertBook(String t, String a, int y, int av) {
        SQLiteDatabase db = getWritableDatabase();
        ContentValues cv = new ContentValues();
        cv.put("title", t); cv.put("author", a);
        cv.put("year", y); cv.put("available", av);
        long r = db.insert(TBL, null, cv);
        db.close();
        return r != -1;
    }

    // READ
    public Cursor viewAll() {
        return getReadableDatabase().rawQuery("SELECT * FROM " + TBL, null);
    }

    // UPDATE
    public boolean updateBook(int id, int av) {
        SQLiteDatabase db = getWritableDatabase();
        ContentValues cv = new ContentValues();
        cv.put("available", av);
        int r = db.update(TBL, cv, "id=?",
                          new String[]{String.valueOf(id)});
        db.close();
        return r > 0;
    }

    // DELETE
    public boolean deleteBook(int id) {
        SQLiteDatabase db = getWritableDatabase();
        int r = db.delete(TBL, "id=?",
                          new String[]{String.valueOf(id)});
        db.close();
        return r > 0;
    }
}
```

**Explanation of Each Step (for 7 marks):**

- Schema with PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT (1)
- Constructor & version handling (1)
- `onCreate()` with CREATE TABLE (1)
- Insert using `ContentValues` (1)
- Read using `Cursor` + `rawQuery` (1)
- Update with WHERE clause (1)
- Delete with WHERE clause (1)

---

#### ✅ Model Solution for (b)

**Firebase RTDB Architecture:**

Firebase RTDB uses a **JSON tree** structure stored in the cloud. The Android client communicates via the Firebase SDK over a **persistent WebSocket** connection. When data at a node changes, all connected clients receive updates through `DataSnapshot` callbacks in real time. The architecture consists of:

- **Firebase Cloud** — hosts the JSON tree.
- **Android Client** — uses `FirebaseDatabase` SDK.
- **Security Rules** — define read/write permissions.

**Code: Push + Read Live**

```java
// WRITE — push() generates a unique key
DatabaseReference ref = FirebaseDatabase.getInstance().getReference("books");
String key = ref.push().getKey();
Book book = new Book("Android Programming", "KTU Press", 2024, true);
ref.child(key).setValue(book);

// READ — real-time listener
ref.addValueEventListener(new ValueEventListener() {
    @Override
    public void onDataChange(DataSnapshot snapshot) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for (DataSnapshot child : snapshot.getChildren()) {
            Book b = child.getValue(Book.class);
            sb.append(b.title).append(" by ").append(b.author).append("\n");
        }
        tvBooks.setText(sb.toString());
    }

    @Override
    public void onCancelled(DatabaseError error) {
        Log.e("FB", error.getMessage());
    }
});
```

